I have been meaning to write a larger piece about megacities for some time. In an effort to start making progresson that and to start gathering some material, I will start doing small autobiographical reviews of some megacities that have made an impression on me.

For now, I am defining a megacity as ’any city with a metro population at or above Paris/London as defined by this pdf.12

  • 1 If that seems unecessary and unfair to Tianjin, I would say that in part the only reason I am including Paris and London on the list at all is they provide a relevant reference point for certain people, not because I think they are defining members of the megacity class.

  • 2 TODO: read this. Also make an automatic tag that looks for ‘UNREAD’ and adds a ‘TODO’ tag.

    • Tokyo-Yokohama

    Jakarta memories 2.1

    Memories

    Spent some time here as a child. I remember taxi rides through dusty highways between skyscrapers, and the golden candle in the center– there was lots of kite-flying. We went to a karaeoke bar and heard a philippino band singing american rock and roll– probably the first live rock music I heard in my life was in bars in Jakarta.

    Delhi memories 3.1, map 3.2

    Memories

    I flew out of Delhi at the end of my post-masters trip. I spent just two weeks there, mostly walking around the markets between the Red Fort and Paharganj where my hostel was. Delhi was pleasant and I thoroughly enjoyed the spice markets and the Jawaharlal Nehru University. They let me see the library, and I unded up browsing their physics section and found some great passages by Bell on the controversies he was involved with in Quantum Mechanics. I’ll upload the text of those passages sometime3 they were fantastic.

  • 3 TODO: upload the text of those passages.

    • I need to give Delhi its time. I was just there to do some pre-return shopping and soak up the last drops of India.

    I believe I should have some google maps data from Delhi.

    Mumbai memories 4.1, map 4.2

    Memories

    I arrived in Mumbai a week after I finished my final defense of my Masters. The moment I finished my masters I had started reading literature nonstop, and so I could hardly bring myself to remember to prepare in any way. I remember being in London before I left, reading Lady Chatterly’s Lover on a bus, dimly aware that something was about to happen. When I arrived in Mumbai airport I realised that I had neglected even to look at the city on google maps, so didn’t even have a vague outline cached on my phone. I couldn’t see evidence of a bus anywere, so I reluctantly queued for a taxi. In the taxi line I asked the people in front of and behind me what was a good district to get started in, and I promptly headed there.

    The city was a chaos4. The taxi driver kept asking me where I wanted to go, and I kept responding with gestures trying to indicate bustle and saying ‘main street’ over and over again. I suppose he got the message, and eventually he gestured for me to get out. The city is a building site, a lot of it is either a slum or that sort of mixed-concrete-blocks, zoneless and haphazard. One of the first things I remember seeing from the highway as we descended into the city proper was a line of people walking along a long, steel passenger bridge, seeming to come from nowhere– might have been a swamp or so– and heading into a railway station, crammed with people. The first street I got out on was crammed wall to wall, and I rushed for the nearest coffee shop. The first one I found was some neoliberal dump, AC too high, possible south Korean inspired hypercapitalist decor. But they had wifi, so I could get my bearings.

  • 4 I vacillated on this repeatedly, almost maddeningly. Before I went, the horrorstories people had told me were so over the top that I basically expected piles of rotting corpses outside the airport. I responded to this with seeming to percieve the whole place as totally underwheling (not a realistic description of Mumbai). Then my first step out of the taxi was a moment of frank disbelief that this could be the main street of the ‘recommended’ district. (I later looked it up and it was indeed one of the nicer parts of town.) Then after my neoliberal latte and wifi, I strolled around feeling almost belligerently at peace (in fact after a week or so there, in order not to lost my mind, I started acting out my belligerent peace quite literally– finding no peace, I made it where I could– sat down in a square foot by a tree and read some poetry in the middle of the crowd– this is how you get by in India. Be belligerently okay with it all until you are.) Much later, after six weeks or so of intense self-imposed exile, when I went back into society to meet a friend, I suddenly had a moment of genuine calm– and I realised ‘wow, okay, it really did take me two full months to become in any way okay with this place’. I would not recommend anyone, even the most experienced traveller, to go to India for less than two months. The very idea that people do this is insane.

    • I messaged some Couchsurfing hosts, had a look at the map, found some interesting looking places and set of to walk around.

    I was quite exhausted and still relatively5 poor, so my plan was to survive for the first month off $100, to set the tone for the rest of my journey. In order to achieve this, I cheated a little: I signed up for Vipassana.

  • 5 I have no illusions about being an unfortunate, but by the standards of europeans I was ‘pennyless’.

    • I had heard about Vipassana from a few friends who had done it in Germany. I believe I went there with the perfect attitude: not expecting anything but a place to stay, but with my natural inclination to doing what is expected of me– I dilligently did whatever they asked, and had a fantastic experience. The Mumbai centers are presumably of a higher standard than those found elsewhere, and the calm oasis in the middle of such a throbbing megacity lent it a quite serious air. You felt like you were doing important business.

    After Vipassana, I foolishly moved to a hostel. This was in part to get some help in figuring out how to get a sim card, which was an enormous pain in the ass at the time. It was a quite horrible experience, especially after Vipassana, and I soon moved to an indian dorm6 where I could work on my reading in peace. It was $3-4 a day for the indian dorm and the bed came with a fan and a lock box. Quite fine, but I wasn’t in the mood for Mumbai– I had far too much reading with me for one thing.

  • 6 this was also essentially a hostel, or a capsule hotel, but I will tend to use the term ‘hostel’ for the kind of backpacker hostel you are familiar with

    Cairo memories 13.1, map 13.2, eat 13.3, sleep 13.4

    Memories

    Cairo! What a city. My most lasting impression was this: why do so many young Europeans who want to experience the exotic, fly all the way to Mumbai or Delhi, when there is this fabulous exotic beast of a city right on their doorstep? It was shocking how close we were to home– the reason we ended up there was the consistently cheap tickets to Sharm-El-Sheik from anywhere in europe– and yet how far we felt.

    I suppose I have always had a clear association with flying east. The 8 hours you spend crossing continents makes you feel like you are suitably far away. So flying what felt like ‘just across the pond’ and yet being somewhere so radically different– interesting!

    Note on the map, I downloaded my historical data from google maps, but unfortunately it was not as high resolution as I expected. A little disappointing, and I have now started using the OSM tracker, for future travel I will have better traces.

    Map

    Code 
    from ipyleaflet import Map, Marker, basemaps, basemap_to_tiles, Polyline, Widget, Popup, AwesomeIcon
from ipywidgets import HTML
import re
import pandas as pd

# Load data from json
file = '/si/_data/lat-lng-time.json'
with open(file, 'r') as f:
    data = f.read()

# Json is of the form {[lat, lng, time], ...}
# Import to pandas
df = pd.read_json(data, orient='records')

# Convert coords
df['lat'] = df['lat'] / 1e7
df['lng'] = df['lng'] / 1e7

# Convert time
df['time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['time'])

# Get coords between lat [29, 31] and lng [30, 32]
df = df[(df['lat'] > 29) & (df['lat'] < 31) & (df['lng'] > 30) & (df['lng'] < 32)]
df.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Sort data into traces
traces = []
# Add first row to first trace
traces.append({'start_time': df['time'][0], 'coords': [(df['lat'][0], df['lng'][0])]})
for i, row in df.iterrows():
    if row['time'] - df.iloc[i-1]['time'] < pd.Timedelta('30 minutes'):
        traces[-1]['coords'].append((row['lat'], row['lng']))
    else:
        traces.append({'start_time': row['time'], 'coords': [(row['lat'], row['lng'])]})

traces = [trace for trace in traces if len(trace['coords']) > 10]

# Select the first entry in febuary
feb_point = df[df['time'] > '2022-02-01'].iloc[0]
# Create a map

m = Map(zoom=12)


first_trace = 2
# Make a line from each trace
for i, trace in enumerate(traces):
    color = '#7c5208'
    if i == first_trace:
        color = 'blue'
    line = Polyline(
        locations=trace['coords'],
        color=color,
        fill=False,
        weight=2,
    )
    m.add_layer(line)

    icon = AwesomeIcon(
        marker_color='darkgreen',
        spin=False
    )

    # Add a marker for each trace
    marker = Marker(
        location=trace['coords'][0],
        draggable=False,
        title=f"Start time: {trace['start_time']}",
        icon=icon,
    )

    # Create a popup
    popup = Popup(
        location=trace['coords'][0],
        child=HTML(f'{trace["start_time"].strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")}'),
        close_button=False,
        auto_close=False,
        close_on_escape_key=False,
    )
    marker.popup = popup

    m.add_layer(marker)

# Center on the start of trace[1]
m.center = traces[1]['coords'][0]
m

    Dar El Salam (دار السلام), ‘Abode of Peace’

    Not to be confused with the Dar es Salaam in Tanzania (or the Muslimgauze album for that matter), this is a district in Cairo.

    The cluster in the south was where we spent the first week. It is something like the highest-density, fastest-growing, youngest population in town. In a phrase, ‘the poor district’. We were asked many times what we were doing there, and told by many people it was dangerous. But, when we met some Expats in a bar in the center, one of them was from Aberdeen– they were all surprised at where we were staying, but when I asked him ‘but, do you really think it is more dangerous than Aberdeen or Glasgow’ he looked offended at the question and said ‘well of course not’.

    Everything is relative, and it is clear that the crime rates in Egypt are very moderate. To us, the district seemed exactly as it was– bustling with youthful exuberance– the transport in the district consisted almost entirely of teenagers in motorized tuktuks with ghetto blasters and LEDs drinking Pepsi, cruising. They were mostly indifferent to our presence– we would ask them to take us somewhere, they would look at one another, laugh, shrug and start driving.

    Hotel Zamalek, and Downtown

    Pyramids of Giza

    Eat

    There are three things to eat in Cairo aside from meat: koshary, sandwiches and sweet potatoes.

    Koshary

    Koshary is a dish that is a staple of the Egyptian diet. It is a mix of carbs: rice, lentils, macaroni and chickpeas. But it isn’t all carbs! It’s also performance. Lets say you got the takeaway; once you have your mass of carbs (in a little grease-paper bowl, like a regular noodle box), you are also given the following: one large baggie of tomato sauce, one baggie of spicy sauce, one baggie of garlic sauce, and a baggy of fried onions.

    The fun is in pouring your ingredients one after another onto your base, and then sprinkling the onions on top, and then consuming it in the fastest way possible.

    Sandwiches

    While I do miss the koshary, for me the sandwiches were the real deal. In imagining them, start with a falafel sandwich. This is actually one of the options, and in many was similar (though superior) to what you would find in europe. Now however, I want you to shrink down the size of the piece of bread considerably, and I want you to remove all the contents, and replace it instead with one of the following: mashed potatoes, foul (refried kidney beans), fried aubergines, fried courgette, shakshuka– or one of the other options that I don’t know how to identify [V: Mousaka!]. So you have your tiny sandwhich with a little bit of friend beans inside it– eat it and have another! Order five if you like, they are cheap as chips and designed for fast, efficient, standing snacking– worthy of Mumbai.

    Walk on, don’t worry– you will see another sandwich place! And another!

    Sweet Potatoes

    Slow cooked sweet potato with spices! Eat it hot, don’t think twice!

    Bubble Tea

    Sleep

    As I was working full time when we were in Cairo, I couldn’t adventure too hard. So we mostly booked AirBnBs or found hotels through Booking. However, Cairo is a fine city for the foot-goer, and we once managed to stumble into a beautiful old, crumbling dame of a hotel– the Nile Zamalek Hotel. We did what you are meant to do in these places, we ordered a room and stayed there for a week, forming a friendly, nodding acquaintance with the concierge and feeling like we were in a classic movie. There is something truly wonderful about finding a place to stay on foot, it will always beat planning, though planning is an occasional necessity.

    Do

    See the pyramids! When I was first in Cairo I refused, or was too stoned and confused and suffering from akathisia or depressed or whatever you are at 20 years old when you haven’t really woken up yet. Well, not this time!

    Victoria wanted to go there and I said, ‘okay, but lets do it properly’. I knew it would be something of a horrorshow, with the skallys and hawkers and hustlers– shafting tourists is practically a national sport in Egypt8– so I thought we should spend at least a day hovering around the district to get the smell of the air. In the end, it was even better– we got a small hotel overlooking the compound and had a whole week basking in the ineffable glory of those monuments. What a place! Things are even stranger than you expect– you understand of course that there are still communities– travellers, performers, poorer districts in Ireland where the horse is still present, but the reality of this in a place like Giza is far odder than you would think.

  • 8 That is not to say that it is dangerous! Here are the brass tacks: in Egypt they are unlikely to assault or rob you as a tourist, but that does not meant that they will treat you with dignity and respect at every turn! In particular, the art of finding the ‘right price’ for things– and consistently getting it, requires constant work– a quick eye, a sharp wit, a good ear– and a mean streak! Because even if you do figure out the right price and some tricks for getting them, you then have to battle with your conscience– do you really want that tea and shisha for less than a dollar, when your monthly income is likely the same as they make in a year? (Short answer, its complicated– yes, often you do want the local price just on principle, but sometimes I find myself wishing I had lost the battle of the wits and gotten shafted a little harder. A delicious samosa in Mumbai from a kind hearted young man that set me back 10p was one of these occasions.)

    • Let me set it up for you: in the Pyramids Complex– a patch of desert surrounded on all sides by a 10m high concrete wall topped with a 4m wire fence containing several pyramids and archeological sites and a deeply unpleasant, presumably 5-star restaurant– there are tourists with thier guides, and there are locals with their horses and camels. The tourists on tours are being sheparded by their guides and kept safe, but there are also roaving bands of lone tourists, all of whom are taxonomically designated as customers for the locals with their horses and camels. The selling of horse and camel rides through the Pyramids Complex seems to be the chief way that the locals benefit economically from their location. This setup, already familiar to me, seemed to my imagination as a classic High Octane Bad Vibe of the tourist-trap variety, and I was not eager to play the role that the locals would obviously want me to play. But enough about me– what I wanted to talk about was, what this setup does for local society. There is a second way in which locals benefit from the pyramids– they run guest houses. We stayed in one and it was very pleasant. But I get the impression that the number of people who hang around in Giza is slim. So what is left is a relatively impoverished district, literally in the shadow of one of the most stunning objects on the earth (and I have seen some things in my time), which has an economic incentive to handle large quantities of camels and horses.

    What I’m getting at here is that the entire district is an extended, sprawling stables. As a farm boy, this was very endearing to me, and I thoroughly enjoyed waking up to the sound of horses galloping in groups past my window. I enjoyed walking through the stable district 100m along the road from our guesthouse. I enjoyed the gangs of pre-teens you would occasionally see who had commandeered a carriage for the evening, barging around the streets with wild abandon. But most of all, I enjoyed the surly, 20-something Arab men who would cruise around town on horseback. This was something I never expected to enjoy so much, and never knew that I had missed! Until I saw it in Giza.

    To give just a bit more context, if you walked for 8 or 9 minutes away from the Complex you would enter Giza proper. The area immediately around the Pyramids is exactly that sort of bizzaro-world that exists in third world countries around UNESCO sites, where the enormity of global inequality is most present, most palpable– and through which veil, one presumes (or one presumes the poor people in the area presume), a person could at these sites most easily pass. The shops have crazy prices and are run by increasingly villainous individuals the closer you get to the gate9. The sheer evil that flickered in the eye of the man who sold me a liter of water for two dollars 50m from the gate– was worth it of course, for the lesson in the shapes and forms of darkness. But if you turn away and walk into Giza, very quickly you will come across a highway, and once you have crossed that highway you are in a very regular part of Cairo. Poor but pround, happy to see you, strange sites on every corner.

  • 9 Exemplified most exquisitely by the KFC that sites directly across from the entrance to the complex– a glowing obelisk of the capitalocene facing off against eternity.

    • Very regular except– for the young men on horseback.

    It was beautiful to me not just because seeing people on horses doing regular people stuff, hanging out, going about the place, seemed like something that all humans should see– its something that was in our culture for millenia, and its a tragedy that we have lost it. But it was also an amusing and deeply characterful lesson in the force of– what to call it, inequality, situations, contingency. That this young man here, on this motorway divider, should be riding a horse about the place as if it was the most regular thing in the world– was due to the fact that tourists found it appropriate to see the pyramids from horseback, and had the cash to actualise their fantasies– and that this was so present, and so consistent that an entire community had grown around the pyramids, a large community of people who, against all odds, in a megacity populated in parts by teenagers in tuktuks high on pepsi, so lost was it in the stream of technofuturism– that here would be the first time I saw regular folks doing people stuff on horseback. Funny.

    The story of the pyramids itself– a great place really– I will leave for another time.

    Conclusions

    I have spent well over a year in megacities– a short time when compared to a random sample of the world population10.

    I feel like there is a lot to be learned about megacities and I look forward to expanding this page.

# Mumbai [memories @sec-mumbai-memories], [map @sec-mumbai-map]

## Memories {#sec-mumbai-memories}

I arrived in Mumbai a week after I finished my final defense of my Masters. The moment I finished my masters I had started reading literature nonstop, and so I could hardly bring myself to remember to prepare in any way. I remember being in London before I left, reading Lady Chatterly's Lover on a bus, dimly aware that something was about to happen. When I arrived in Mumbai airport I realised that I had neglected even to look at the city on google maps, so didn't even have a vague outline cached on my phone. I couldn't see evidence of a bus anywere, so I reluctantly queued for a taxi. In the taxi line I asked the people in front of and behind me what was a good district to get started in, and I promptly headed there.

The city was a chaos[^chaos]. The taxi driver kept asking me where I wanted to go, and I kept responding with gestures trying to indicate bustle and saying 'main street' over and over again. I suppose he got the message, and eventually he gestured for me to get out. The city is a building site, a lot of it is either a slum or that sort of mixed-concrete-blocks, zoneless and haphazard. One of the first things I remember seeing from the highway as we descended into the city proper was a line of people walking along a long, steel passenger bridge, seeming to come from nowhere-- might have been a swamp or so-- and heading into a railway station, crammed with people. The first street I got out on was crammed wall to wall, and I rushed for the nearest coffee shop. The first one I found was some neoliberal dump, AC too high, possible south Korean inspired hypercapitalist decor. But they had wifi, so I could get my bearings.

I messaged some Couchsurfing hosts, had a look at the map, found some interesting looking places and set of to walk around.

[^chaos]: I vacillated on this repeatedly, almost maddeningly. Before I went, the horrorstories people had told me were so over the top that I basically expected piles of rotting corpses outside the airport. I responded to this with seeming to percieve the whole place as totally underwheling (not a realistic description of Mumbai). Then my first step out of the taxi was a moment of frank disbelief that this could be the main street of the 'recommended' district. (I later looked it up and it was indeed one of the nicer parts of town.) Then after my neoliberal latte and wifi, I strolled around feeling almost belligerently at peace (in fact after a week or so there, in order not to lost my mind, I started acting out my belligerent peace quite literally-- finding no peace, I made it where I could-- sat down in a square foot by a tree and read some poetry in the middle of the crowd-- this is how you get by in India. Be belligerently okay with it all until you are.) Much later, after six weeks or so of intense self-imposed exile, when I went back into society to meet a friend, I suddenly had a moment of genuine calm-- and I realised 'wow, okay, it really did take me two full months to become in any way okay with this place'. I would not recommend anyone, even the most experienced traveller, to go to India for less than two months. The very idea that people do this is insane.

I was quite exhausted and still relatively[^rel] poor, so my plan was to survive for the first month off \$100, to set the tone for the rest of my journey. In order to achieve this, I cheated a little: I signed up for Vipassana.

[^rel]: I have no illusions about being an unfortunate, but by the standards of europeans I was 'pennyless'.

I had heard about Vipassana from a few friends who had done it in Germany. I believe I went there with the perfect attitude: not expecting anything but a place to stay, but with my natural inclination to doing what is expected of me-- I dilligently did whatever they asked, and had a fantastic experience. The Mumbai centers are presumably of a higher standard than those found elsewhere, and the calm oasis in the middle of such a throbbing megacity lent it a quite serious air. You felt like you were doing important business.

After Vipassana, I foolishly moved to a hostel. This was in part to get some help in figuring out how to get a sim card, which was an enormous pain in the ass at the time. It was a quite horrible experience, especially after Vipassana, and I soon moved to an indian dorm[^dorm] where I could work on my reading in peace. It was \$3-4 a day for the indian dorm and the bed came with a fan and a lock box. Quite fine, but I wasn't in the mood for Mumbai-- I had far too much reading with me for one thing.

[^dorm]: this was also essentially a hostel, or a capsule hotel, but I will tend to use the term 'hostel' for the kind of backpacker hostel you are familiar with

# Cairo [memories @sec-cairo-memories], [map @sec-cairo-map], [eat @sec-cairo-eat], [sleep @sec-cairo-sleep]


## Memories {#sec-cairo-memories}

Cairo! What a city. My most lasting impression was this: why do so many young Europeans who want to experience the exotic, fly all the way to Mumbai or Delhi, when there is this fabulous exotic beast of a city right on their doorstep? It was shocking how close we were to home-- the reason we ended up there was the consistently cheap tickets to Sharm-El-Sheik from anywhere in europe-- and yet how far we felt.

I suppose I have always had a clear association with flying east. The 8 hours you spend crossing continents makes you feel like you are suitably far away. So flying what felt like 'just across the pond' and yet being somewhere so radically different-- interesting!

Note on the map, I downloaded my historical data from google maps, but unfortunately it was not as high resolution as I expected. A little disappointing, and I have now started using the OSM tracker, for future travel I will have better traces.

## Map {#sec-cairo-map}

{{< include _Megacity_Maps.qmd >}}

### Dar El Salam (دار السلام), 'Abode of Peace'

> Not to be confused with the [Dar es Salaam](W!) in Tanzania (or [the Muslimgauze album](https://www.discogs.com/release/170171-Muslimgauze-Dar-Es-Salaam) for that matter), this is a district in Cairo.

The cluster in the south was where we spent the first week. It is something like the highest-density, fastest-growing, youngest population in town. In a phrase, 'the poor district'. We were asked many times what we were doing there, and told by many people it was dangerous. But, when we met some Expats in a bar in the center, one of them was from Aberdeen-- they were all surprised at where we were staying, but when I asked him 'but, do you really think it is more dangerous than Aberdeen or Glasgow' he looked offended at the question and said 'well of course not'.

Everything is relative, and it is clear that the crime rates in Egypt are very moderate. To us, the district seemed exactly as it was-- bustling with youthful exuberance-- the transport in the district consisted almost entirely of teenagers in [motorized tuktuks with ghetto blasters and LEDs](Essays/ThirdWorldTechnology) drinking Pepsi, cruising. They were mostly indifferent to our presence-- we would ask them to take us somewhere, they would look at one another, laugh, shrug and start driving.

## Eat {#sec-cairo-eat}

There are three things to eat in Cairo [aside from meat](/Essays/Vegetarianism): koshary, sandwiches and sweet potatoes.

### Koshary

Koshary is a dish that is a staple of the Egyptian diet. It is a mix of carbs: rice, lentils, macaroni and chickpeas. But it isn't all carbs! It's also performance. Lets say you got the takeaway; once you have your mass of carbs (in a little grease-paper bowl, like a regular noodle box), you are also given the following: one large baggie of tomato sauce, one baggie of spicy sauce, one baggie of garlic sauce, and a baggy of fried onions.

The fun is in pouring your ingredients one after another onto your base, and then sprinkling the onions on top, and then consuming it in the fastest way possible.

### Sandwiches

While I do miss the koshary, for me the sandwiches were the real deal. In imagining them, start with a falafel sandwich. This is actually one of the options, and in many was similar (though superior) to what you would find in europe. Now however, I want you to shrink down the size of the piece of bread considerably, and I want you to remove all the contents, and replace it instead with one of the following: mashed potatoes, foul (refried kidney beans), fried aubergines, fried courgette, shakshuka-- or one of the other options that I don't know how to identify [V: Mousaka!]. So you have your tiny sandwhich with a little bit of friend beans inside it-- eat it and have another! Order five if you like, they are cheap as chips and designed for fast, efficient, standing snacking-- worthy of [Mumbai](/Reviews/Megacities#Mumbai).

Walk on, don't worry-- you will see another sandwich place! And another!

### Sweet Potatoes

Slow cooked sweet potato with spices! Eat it hot, don't think twice!

## Sleep {#sec-cairo-sleep}

As I was [working full time](/Essays/Work#Hypermile) when we were in Cairo, I couldn't adventure too hard. So we mostly booked [AirBnBs](www.airbnb.com) or found hotels through [Booking](www.booking.com). However, Cairo is a fine city for the foot-goer, and we once managed to stumble into a beautiful old, crumbling dame of a hotel-- the [Nile Zamalek Hotel](https://nilezamalekhotel.com-cairo.com/). We did what you are meant to do in these places, we ordered a room and stayed there for a week, forming a friendly, nodding acquaintance with the concierge and feeling like we were in a classic movie. There is something truly wonderful about finding a place to stay on foot, it will always beat planning, though planning is an occasional necessity.

## Do

See the pyramids! When I was [first in Cairo](/Travel/Journeys#winter-2010-2011) I refused, or was too stoned and confused and suffering from akathisia or depressed or whatever you are at 20 years old when you haven't really woken up yet. Well, not this time!

Victoria wanted to go there and I said, 'okay, but lets do it properly'. I knew it would be something of a horrorshow, with the skallys and hawkers and hustlers-- shafting tourists is practically a national sport in Egypt[^shafting]-- so I thought we should spend at least a day hovering around the district to get the smell of the air. In the end, it was even better-- we got a small hotel overlooking the compound and had a whole week basking in the ineffable glory of those monuments. What a place! Things are even stranger than you expect-- you understand of course that there are still communities-- [travellers](???), [performers](???), [poorer districts in Ireland](???) where the horse is still present, but the reality of this in a place like Giza is far odder than you would think.

Let me set it up for you: in the Pyramids Complex-- a patch of desert surrounded on all sides by a 10m high concrete wall topped with a 4m wire fence containing several pyramids and archeological sites and a deeply unpleasant, presumably 5-star restaurant-- there are tourists with thier guides, and there are locals with their horses and camels. The tourists on tours are being sheparded by their guides and kept safe, but there are also roaving bands of lone tourists, all of whom are taxonomically designated as customers for the locals with their horses and camels. The selling of horse and camel rides through the Pyramids Complex seems to be the chief way that the locals benefit economically from their location. This setup, already familiar to me, seemed to my imagination as a classic High Octane Bad Vibe of the tourist-trap variety, and I was not eager to play the role that the locals would obviously want me to play. But enough about me-- what I wanted to talk about was, what this setup does for local society. There is a second way in which locals benefit from the pyramids-- they run guest houses. We stayed in one and it was very pleasant. But I get the impression that the number of people who hang around in Giza is slim. So what is left is a relatively impoverished district, literally in the shadow of one of the most stunning objects on the earth (and I have seen some things in my time), which has an economic incentive to handle large quantities of camels and horses.

[^shafting]: That is not to say that it is dangerous! Here are the brass tacks: in Egypt they are unlikely to assault or rob you as a tourist, but that does not meant that they will treat you with dignity and respect at every turn! In particular, the art of finding the 'right price' for things-- and consistently getting it, requires constant work-- a quick eye, a sharp wit, a good ear-- and a mean streak! Because even if you do figure out the right price and [some tricks](/Travel/Tips#Price) for getting them, you then have to battle with your conscience-- do you really want that tea and shisha for less than a dollar, when your monthly income is likely the same as they make in a year? (Short answer, its complicated-- yes, often you do want the local price just on principle, but sometimes I find myself wishing I had lost the battle of the wits and gotten shafted a little harder. A delicious samosa in Mumbai from a kind hearted young man that set me back 10p was one of these occasions.)

What I'm getting at here is that the entire district is an extended, sprawling stables. As a farm boy, this was very endearing to me, and I thoroughly enjoyed waking up to the sound of horses galloping in groups past my window. I enjoyed walking through the stable district 100m along the road from our guesthouse. I enjoyed the gangs of pre-teens you would occasionally see who had commandeered a carriage for the evening, barging around the streets with wild abandon. But most of all, I enjoyed the surly, 20-something Arab men who would cruise around town on horseback. This was something I never expected to enjoy so much, and never knew that I had missed! Until I saw it in Giza.

To give just a bit more context, if you walked for 8 or 9 minutes away from the Complex you would enter Giza proper. The area immediately around the Pyramids is exactly that sort of bizzaro-world that exists in third world countries around UNESCO sites, where the enormity of global inequality is most present, most palpable-- and through which veil, one presumes (or one presumes the poor people in the area presume), a person could at these sites most easily pass. The shops have crazy prices and are run by increasingly villainous individuals the closer you get to the gate[^KFC]. The sheer evil that flickered in the eye of the man who sold me a liter of water for two dollars 50m from the gate-- was worth it of course, for the lesson in the shapes and forms of darkness. But if you turn away and walk into Giza, very quickly you will come across [a highway](??? link to the highway on google), and once you have crossed that highway you are in a very regular part of Cairo. Poor but pround, happy to see you, strange sites on every corner.

[^KFC]: Exemplified most exquisitely by the KFC that sites directly across from the entrance to the complex-- a glowing obelisk of the capitalocene facing off against eternity.

Very regular except-- for the young men on horseback.

It was beautiful to me not just because seeing people on horses doing regular people stuff, hanging out, going about the place, seemed like something that all humans should see-- its something that was in our culture for millenia, and its a tragedy that we have lost it. But it was also an amusing and deeply characterful lesson in the force of-- what to call it, inequality, situations, contingency. That this young man here, on this motorway divider, should be riding a horse about the place as if it was the most regular thing in the world-- was due to the fact that tourists found it appropriate to see the pyramids from horseback, and had the cash to actualise their fantasies-- and that this was so present, and so consistent that an entire community had grown around the pyramids, a large community of people who, against all odds, in a megacity populated in parts by teenagers in tuktuks high on pepsi, so lost was it in the stream of technofuturism-- that here would be the first time I saw regular folks doing people stuff on horseback. Funny.

The story of the pyramids itself-- a great place really-- I will leave for another time.

# Conclusions
I have spent well over a year in megacities-- a short time when compared to a random sample of the world population[^???].

[^???]: TODO, does this mean anything?

I have visited [16/34] of the worlds megacities. There are around 10 more that are high on my list which I should get to in the next decade. I think Moscow and Tehran are the only major difficulties-- but I am writing this in the time of the [Mahsa Amini protests](W!) so lets see.

I feel like there is a lot to be learned about megacities and I look forward to expanding this page.
